
@startuml

' Define classes and their attributes
class Faculty {
  - name: String
  - numberOfInstitutes: int
  - dean: Employee
}

class Institute {
  - name: String
  - address: String
  - faculty: Faculty
}

class Employee {
  - socialSecurityNumber: String
  - name: String
  - email: String
  - type: String
}

class ResearchAssistant {
  + fieldOfResearch: String
  - projects: List<Project>
  - courses: List<Course>
}

class Lecturer {
  - courses: List<Course>
}

class Project {
  - name: String
  - startDate: Date
  - endDate: Date
  - hours: int
}

class Course {
  - courseId: String
  - name: String
  - weeklyDuration: int
}

' Associations
Faculty "1" -- "0..*" Institute : consists of
Institute "1" -- "1" Faculty : belongs to
Faculty "1" -- "1" Employee : has dean
Employee "1" -- "0..*" ResearchAssistant : is a
ResearchAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Project : is involved in
ResearchAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Course : teaches
Course "1" -- "1" Lecturer : taught by

@enduml

### Notes:
- `ResearchAssistant` inherits from `Employee`.
- `Lecturer` is a specialization of `ResearchAssistant`, which implies a **generalization** relationship.
- `Project` is associated with `ResearchAssistant` (a RA can be involved in multiple projects).
- `Course` is associated with `Lecturer` (a lecturer teaches one or more courses).
- The relationships reflect the composition and aggregation as per the domain model.

